<p>
  JavaScript expressions follow the standard order of operations, so even though <code>-</code> is written before
  <code>*</code>, the multiplication is carried out first.
</p>

<pre>
500 - 10 * 5 // 450</pre>

<p>
  Brackets <code>()</code> can be used to group arithmetic operations, and take precedence over the standard order or
  operations.
</p>

<p>
  By default, JavaScript comes with the <code>Math</code> object. It can be used to manipulate numbers in many different
  ways, the full list of which can be found <a
    href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Math">here</a>. One function
  of the <code>Math</code> object is to round decimal numbers, using <code>Math.round()</code>.
</p>

